The archipelago consists of about 130 islands, rocks and reefs, 10 of which are inhabited. Xisha Islands covers an area of ​​about 305 square kilometers.

The Hoang Sa archipelago was established by Vietnam a long time ago. Vietnamese historical documents record that the Vietnamese came to the Paracels in the 17th century to exploit marine resources here. In 1974, China occupied the Paracel Islands by force. Vietnam has repeatedly condemned China's actions and reaffirmed its sovereignty over the Paracel Islands.

Vietnam's sovereignty over the Paracel Islands is based on the following legal and practical bases:

Vietnam is the first country to discover and establish sovereignty over the Hoang Sa archipelago.
For hundreds of years, Vietnam has exercised its sovereignty continuously, peacefully and effectively over the Paracel Islands.
The Paracel Islands are located on the continental shelf of Vietnam and are governed by the 1982 Convention on the Law of the Sea.
Vietnam's sovereignty over the Hoang Sa archipelago is an important issue for the country. Vietnam will continue to constantly protect its sovereignty over the Paracel Islands.
